<Base
  title="About — Stuart Robinson"
  description="15 years building platforms for energy, travel, healthcare, and startups. Now building Helioy."
>
  <article class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 pt-12 pb-20">
    <header class="mb-10">
      <a
        href="/"
        class="text-sm text-white/30 hover:text-white/60 transition-colors"
        >&larr; Back</a
      >
      <h1 class="mt-6 text-3xl font-bold text-white/90 tracking-tight">
        About
      </h1>
    </header>

    <div class="prose prose-invert prose-lg max-w-none">
      <p>
        I spent 15 years building platforms for energy, travel, healthcare, and
        startups across three continents. Kubernetes clusters, data streaming
        pipelines, infrastructure that had to hold up at scale. That work taught
        me something about instrumentation and monitoring: how you know a system
        is healthy, how you know it's degrading, and what happens when you stop
        paying attention.
      </p>

      <p>Now I build Helioy.</p>

      <p>
        The conviction driving it: the fundamental unit of AI system quality is
        signal-per-token. Not model size. Not tool count. Not context window
        length. The density of useful signal in every token the model processes.
        Every token counts.
      </p>

      <p>
        Most agent frameworks solve execution. Helioy is working to solve
        something upstream. How does a system of agents sustain itself? Not just
        execute tasks, but maintain coherence across sessions, evolve its own
        capabilities, and form organizational memory that compounds rather than
        fragments. Most current "agents" are open-loop pipelines pretending to be
        autonomous systems. Helioy is building toward something closer to
        digital life.
      </p>

      <p>
        The theoretical foundation comes from autocatalytic closure: the same
        formal framework that explains how living systems bootstrap from
        chemistry into self-sustaining biology. A minimum autocatalytic set needs
        five capabilities: observe, deliberate, act, evaluate, remember. Each
        Helioy component maps to one of these. frontmatter-matters gives agents
        structural perception of code. context-matters persists decisions and
        lessons across scopes. attention-matters builds reflective memory on a
        geometric hypersphere, organizational identity that shapes every
        interaction without being consumed by it. A message bus carries signals
        between agents. An orchestrator routes context under token pressure.
      </p>

      <p>
        The CRITIC sits at the center. It evolves the system genome: skills,
        prompts, agent definitions, configurations, using the owner's values as
        the fitness function. The owner curates the terrain. The system evolves
        to thrive on it.
      </p>

      <p>
        I own the what and why. The agents own the how. The question driving all
        of it: can an agent system achieve the property of self-sustenance that
        living systems have? And can we measure when it does?
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
